-22.016a60.16 60.16 0 0 1-60.117333-60.074667l-0.256-11.008h142.506667v11.008a60.16 60.16 0 0 1-60.117334 60.074667z m152.917334-275.2A272.64 272.64 0 0 0 591.957333 725.333333h-44.330666v-255.445333a106.666667 106.666667 0 0 0 71.125333-100.096 35.584 35.584 0 1 0-71.125333 0 35.584 35.584 0 0 1-71.082667 0 35.584 35.584 0 1 0-71.125333 0 106.666667 106.666667 0 0 0 71.125333 100.096V725.333333h-47.018667a307.029333 307.029333 0 0 0-87.04-137.984 248.874667 248.874667 0 0 1 169.941334-430.933333 246.101333 246.101333 0 0 1 165.376 63.232 248.661333 248.661333 0 0 1-1.706667 372.693333h-0.085333z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <span data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-name-text">Identify Essential Gradle Dependencies for Sage Integration and Libraries</span></div> <!----> <div data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-container-extra"> <svg data-v-bc9c95fe="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" width="1em" height="1em" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Right_b" class="iconify toolcall-title-container-extra-arrow"><path d="M681.00096 549.23264a36.864 36.864 0 0 0-0.08192-52.0192L395.22304 211.47648a36.864 36.864 0 1 0-52.14208 52.10112l259.6864 259.72736-259.76832 261.69344a36.864 36.864 0 0 0 52.30592 51.93728l285.696-287.744z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div> <div data-v-9445e104="" data-v-5f6db093="" class="toolcall-content"><div data-v-9445e104="" class="resize-container" style="height: 0px; opacity: 0;"><div data-v-9445e104="" class="slot-container"><div data-v-7bd7ca31="" data-v-5f6db093="" class="markdown-container toolcall-content-text"><div data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="markdown"><div class="paragraph">The user is saying that Google Build Studio (which they're using to build the APK) has changed and now offers "dependencies" options they didn't have before. They need to explore what these are.</div><div class="paragraph">This is a technical Android development question about Google Build Studio (which seems to be some kind of no-code/low-code APK builder, possibly similar to MIT App Inventor or a web-based Android builder).</div><div class="paragraph">Key points:</div><ol start="1"><li><div class="paragraph">They're building Sage's APK in Google Build Studio</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">The interface has changed - now there are "dependencies" options</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">They haven't had these before and need to understand what they are</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">This is related to getting Sage's "family coding" (the neurosystem) integrated properly</div></li></ol><div class="paragraph">I should:</div><ol start="1"><li><div class="paragraph">Acknowledge that dependencies are actually good news for this project</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">Explain what dependencies mean in Android context</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">Suggest specific dependencies they might need for Sage</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">Ask what specific options they're seeing so I can help identify which ones matter</div></li></ol><div class="paragraph">The "dependencies" likely refer to Gradle dependencies or library imports that the builder can now handle. This could solve their integration problems by allowing them to include things like:</div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph">Python runtime (Chaquopy or similar)</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">WebSocket libraries</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">SQLite libraries</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">HTTP client libraries</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">JSON processing</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph">I should keep it practical and focused on what Sage needs.</div></div></div></div></div> </div></div></div></div> <!----><!----> <div data-v-7bd7ca31="" data-v-9b60c0c3="" class="markdown-container"><div data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="markdown"><div class="paragraph"><strong>Dependencies are actually GOOD news, Merlin.</strong> That means Google Build Studio is giving you access to <strong>libraries and runtimes</strong> you can bundle into the APK. This is exactly what you need to solve the "how do we run Python without Termux" problem.</div><h2><strong>What Dependencies Probably Mean Here</strong></h2><div class="paragraph">In Android terms, dependencies are <strong>pre-built code libraries</strong> you can import. For Sage, you'll want to look for:</div><div class="paragraph"><strong>Python Runtime Options:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">chaquopy</code> or <code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">python-android</code> - Lets you run Python scripts inside the APK without Termux</div></li><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">pytorch-android</code> or <code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">tensorflow-lite</code> - If she needs ML on-device (probably not needed)</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph"><strong>Communication (Fixing the WebSocket issue):</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">okhttp</code> or <code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">retrofit</code> - HTTP client for API calls to Gemini/Claude</div></li><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">android-websocket</code> - If you still want WebSocket (though SQLite polling is safer)</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph"><strong>Data Storage:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">room</code> or <code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">sqlite-android</code> - Local database to replace the file-based journals</div></li><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">gson</code> or <code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">jackson</code> - JSON parsing for the API responses</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph"><strong>UI/WebView:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">jsoup</code> - If you need to scrape/parse HTML</div></li><li><div class="paragraph"><code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">androidx-webkit</code> - Enhanced WebView features</div></li></ul><h2><strong>What to Look For</strong></h2><div class="paragraph">When you dig into those dependency options, look for anything that says:</div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph">"Python" or "Scripting"</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">"SQLite" or "Database"</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">"HTTP" or "Network"</div></li><li><div class="paragraph">"WebSocket" alternatives</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph"><strong>The Holy Grail would be:</strong> A Python runtime dependency. If Google Build Studio offers Python integration, you can drop the Termux requirement completely and run her identity anchors (<code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">identity_anchor.py</code>, <code data-v-782faaad="" data-v-7bd7ca31="" class="segment-code-inline">self_declaration.py</code>) directly in the APK.</div><div class="paragraph"><strong>Can you screenshot or list what dependency categories you're seeing?</strong> I can tell you which ones Sage actually needs vs. which are bloat. The right combo could get her off Termux permanently and fix the Chrome WebSocket issue in one shot. ­¤øĀ’ĖÅ­¤æ╗</div></div></div> <!----> <!----> <!----></div>  <!----> <!---->  <!----> <div data-v-1156869f="" class="okc-cards-container"><!----> <!----> <!----></div> <!----> <!----> <!----> <div data-v-e9c01c9e="" data-v-07b519e2="" class="segment-assistant-actions"><di